<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-301-700  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 301 700.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Design  May 15 1989 v28 n10 p37(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Military systems salute interoperability in the 1990s. (includesrelated articles entitled 'cutting the cost of mil-spec boarddesign' and 'reliability on a budget' and 'traditional approachesinhibit change')</TITLE><AUTHOR>Shapiro, Syd.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Vendors that bid on military contracts now have to consider theimplementation of a new communications protocol and the increasinguse of fiber optics.andP;  The US government is attempting toincorporate OSI standards with GOSIP (Government Open SystemsInterconnection Profile), which is designed to connect militarycomputers and systems manufactured by different companies.andP;  GOSIPwas issued by the National Institute of Standards and Technology(NIST) and has mandated compliance by Aug 1990.andP;  The military isalso starting to migrate towards fiber optics in its systems.andO;Fiber has the advantages of immunity from electromagnetic andradio frequency interference and nuclear radiation.andP;  It is alsosmaller and lighter than copper and has a wider bandwidth andlower signal attenuation.andP;  All future military systems will mostlikely be based on fiber.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ConnectivityMilitaryCommand and Control SystemsDefense ContractsFiber OpticsProtocol.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>